Top highlights

  • NO ICE PACKS, EVER AGAIN! - The FRIO wallet eliminates the need for ice packs. With no ice, your medication will not freeze - and your storage will be stress-free!
  • WATER ACTIVATED COOLING - The FRIO evaporative cooler activates by simply soaking in water for 10-15 minutes - and then cools for 2-4 days. To re-activate simply soak again.
  • THE DUO FRIO IS IDEAL FOR CARRYING 2 PENS OR VIALS - FRIO comes in many different sizes to accommodate your medication needs. Not the right FRIO size? See the size guide below.
  • TRAVEL SMART, TRAVEL FRIO - Jet set without limits! Enjoy stress free adventures with our travel insulin cooler. Get secure, on-the-go insulin storage without the fridge. TSA friendly.
  • EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS - Without the need for refrigeration or electricity, the FRIO is the ideal way to keep your critical medication cool and safe during a disaster. The FRIO provides you with freedom, convenience, and peace of mind!

Additional details

Safety Information

Do not carry or store in an airtight or waterproof container when activated. Frios need to breathe. They work by evaporation and need to be in contact with the air. Carrying in hand luggage or a pocket is satisfactory.

Ingredients

Each pack consists of two parts: 1) Cambrelle outer cover; 2) Inner Frio pouch made of poly-cotton with panels containing crystals, which are non-toxic and non-flammable (our safety data sheet is available if required)

Directions

Soak product in cold water according to enclosed directions. Spread crystals evenly through pouch. Gently towel dry. Place medication in activated pouch and and then place in outer Cambrelle cover.

Legal Disclaimer

From the brand

Since 1996

FRIO provides people with diabetes and other medication users with the ultimate accessory to keep their medication cool and safe.

  2. FRIO innovates medication cooling, liberating insulin users from traditional constraints. During disasters, it emerges as a life-saving solution, ensuring the safety of life-sustaining medications. The brand engages communities, collaborates with corporations, and advocates for emergency preparedness, embodying values of innovation, compassion, and a strong commitment to saving lives.

  4. Why Choose FRIO?

    FRIO is different from other medication coolers because it never needs ice packs or refrigeration. This differentiator cuts the invisible chain to refrigeration, allowing a person who is dependent on insulin the convenience and freedom that he could never possibly enjoy before.

    Our Mission

    Save lives with insulin cooling.

    Core Values

    Innovation, compassion, community, life-saving commitment, responsibility, preparedness advocacy.

  5. Puerto Rico, Maria, and FRIO

    FRIO stands out from other medication coolers as it doesn't require ice or refrigeration, offering unprecedented freedom to insulin-dependent individuals. Its value was proven during disasters like Hurricane Maria in Puerto Rico, where it ensured life-saving medications like insulin remained cool without power. Over 25,000 FRIOs were distributed in Puerto Rico post-hurricane, effectively addressing the challenge of maintaining insulin efficacy for the island's diabetic population, demonstrating FRIO's critical role in emergency preparedness.

  6. This summarizes our rewarding experience in achieving our goal.

    In the aftermath of the hurricane, we tried contacting major organizations for assistance but faced delays with larger entities. Direct shipping of FRIOs to Puerto Rico was also not viable initially due to disrupted courier services and distribution challenges, preventing us from ensuring the FRIOs reached those in need.

    We contacted the Diabetes coalition of JDRF, ADA, and Insulin for Life. Though we aimed for a broader collaboration, we donated a significant number of FRIOs, which Insulin for Life distributed in the island.

  7. The need for action was urgent. As media highlighted the crisis, we were inundated with offers to help. Collaboration between JDRF's Linda Popky, Carb DM's Tamar Sofer-Geri, and our own Lisa Katzki led to a fundraising effort on Carb DM's site, quickly raising funds for 1,000 FRIOs for Puerto Rico. Yankee All-Star Jorge Posada and Dr. Luis Perez of the Puerto Rico Diabetes Association facilitated transportation and distribution.

  8. Grassroots and Corporate Support for Puerto Rico's Emergency Needs

    Numerous established and new grassroots organizations nationwide also took similar actions. They also raised funds from hundreds of generous donors and sponsored FRIOs to be sent to Puerto Rico.

    The private sector also rose to the occasion. A healthcare company chartered a private plane and sent 1,000 FRIOs and other emergency supplies to its constituents in Puerto Rico. The international pharmaceutical company, Sanofi, sponsored 15,000 FRIOs - to be handed out to those in Puerto Rico who needed them!

  9. As services resumed, capitalism contributed, with a major distributor buying thousands of FRIOs for island pharmacies and new distributors emerging to meet the need.

    Being part of this solution was rewarding, underscoring the importance of emergency preparedness for those reliant on temperature-sensitive medications. If not now, when?

    I must admit that I was skeptical that this would actually work as described, but simply put, it does and I love it. I bought this because I fly a lot and didn't want to deal with products with ice packs, especially going through TSA (I know ice packs are permitted by... See more
    I must admit that I was skeptical that this would actually work as described, but simply put, it does and I love it. I bought this because I fly a lot and didn't want to deal with products with ice packs, especially going through TSA (I know ice packs are permitted by TSA for medicine but the process can still be a pain). This is much more convenient and compact and keeps things cold for several days (not hours) without refrigeration. There is no melting or sweating of ice packs to deal with and you don't need to worry about ice packs that can freeze your medicine. I have been using it since November, and it worked for all of my trips without an issue (even to several hot locations in the Caribbean). Simply soak the interior pouch in water, lay it on a paper towel to soak up any excess water, slide your medicine in the pouch, slide the pouch into the outer case and go. The product has some type of crystals in the interior pouch lining that swell when soaked in water and turn into a gel like substance. When you are finished using it, you just let it sit out and air dry and the gel turns back into crystals. It is so simple, convenient and reusable.

  • Golden Lover
    5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    Work great!
    Reviewed in the United States on May 28, 2014
    Color: Black
    I have used Frio cooling cases for years and they work really well. They are made to keep insulin cool but will NOT keep anything cold, at refrigerator temperature nor frozen. Insulin is supposed to be stored long-term in a refrigerator but an open bottle or pen should be... See more
    I have used Frio cooling cases for years and they work really well. They are made to keep insulin cool but will NOT keep anything cold, at refrigerator temperature nor frozen. Insulin is supposed to be stored long-term in a refrigerator but an open bottle or pen should be kept at room temperature or slightly cooler. Frio cases use evaporation and work perfectly for this purpose.

    If you don't follow the directions the case won't keep anything cool so I will do a quick re-cap of the directions for anyone who might have lost their directions.

    Remove the inner case from the Velcro-close outer cover. Place the inner pouch into a sink and fill the sink with enough water to cover the pouch. Allow it to absorb water until it is nice and puffy but not rigid, usually about 10 minutes. I don't set a timer but just check it after a few minutes. If it gets too rigid you can gently squeeze it to remove some of the water. Drain the water from the sink and let the pouch sit for a few minutes, then wipe lightly with a towel. Place the insulin or pens into the soaked pouch and put all of that into the cover. This will NOT leak! DO NOT put it into a Ziploc bag or other plastic.

    The really important thing to remember is that this works by evaporation so air needs to get to the pouch. I keep mine in a loosely packed tote bag or a purse, or on the car seat. Don't pack it into a suitcase or tightly closed bag because it won't work. I'm not sure if this will work on hot summer days when I need to leave my insulin in a closed-up car for several hours so I will put the whole thing into a cooler with some ice packs. The padded pouch protects the insulin from freezing against the ice packs.

    I have never had one of these stop working so I don't know how long they can last. I usually end up losing mine and having to buy a new one.
